<check_type:"VMware">

<report type:"PASSED">
  description : "DISA STIG VMware vSphere ESXi 6 Security Technical Implementation Guide Version 1 Release 5"
</report>

<report type:"WARNING">
  description : "ESXI-06-000001 - The VMM must limit the number of concurrent sessions to ten for all accounts and/or account types by enabling lockdown mode."
  info        : "Enabling lockdown mode disables direct access to an ESXi host requiring the host be managed remotely from vCenter Server. This is done to ensure the roles and access controls implemented in vCenter are always enforced and users cannot bypass them by logging into a host directly. By forcing all interaction to occur through vCenter Server, the risk of someone inadvertently attaining elevated privileges or performing tasks that are not properly audited is greatly reduced.

NOTE: Nessus has not performed this check. Please review the benchmark to ensure target compliance."
  solution    : "From the vSphere Web Client select the ESXi Host and go to Manage >> Settings >> System >> Security Profile.  Click edit on 'Lockdown Mode' and set to Enabled (Normal or Strict).

or

From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESXi host run the following commands:

$level = 'lockdownNormal' OR 'lockdownStrict'
$vmhost = Get-VMHost -Name <hostname> | Get-View
$lockdown = Get-View $vmhost.ConfigManager.HostAccessManager
$lockdown.ChangeLockdownMode($level)

Note: In strict lockdown mode, which is new in vSphere 6.0, the DCUI service is stopped. If the connection to vCenter Server is lost and the vSphere Web Client is no longer available, the ESXi host becomes inaccessible."
  reference   : "CAT|II,CCI|CCI-000054,Group-ID|V-63147,Rule-ID|SV-77637r1_rule,STIG-ID|ESXI-06-000001,Vuln-ID|V-63147"
  see_also    : "https://dl.dod.cyber.mil/wp-content/uploads/stigs/zip/U_VMware_vSphere_6-0_ESXi_V1R5_STIG.zip"
</report>

<custom_item>
  type        : AUDIT_ESX
  description : "ESXI-06-000002 - The system must verify the DCUI.Access list."
  info        : "Lockdown mode disables direct host access requiring that admins manage hosts from vCenter Server.  However, if a host becomes isolated from vCenter Server, the admin is locked out and can no longer manage the host. If you are using normal lockdown mode, you can avoid becoming locked out of an ESXi host that is running in lockdown mode, by setting DCUI.Access to a list of highly trusted users who can override lockdown mode and access the DCUI. The DCUI is not running in strict lockdown mode."
  solution    : "From the vSphere Client select the ESXi Host and go to Configuration >> Advanced Settings.  Select the DCUI.Access value and configure it to root.

or

From a PowerCLI command prompt while connected to the ESXi host run the following command:

Get-VMHost | Get-AdvancedSetting -Name DCUI.Access | Set-AdvancedSetting -Value 'root'"
  reference   : "800-171|3.1.1,800-53|AC-3,CAT|III,CCI|CCI-000366,CN-L3|8.1.10.2(c),CN-L3|8.1.4.11(b),CN-L3|8.1.4.2(f),CN-L3|8.5.3.1,CN-L3|8.5.4.1(a),CSF|PR.AC-4,CSF|PR.PT-3,Group-ID|V-63173,ISO/IEC-27001|A.9.4.1,ISO/IEC-27001|A.9.4.5,ITSG-33|AC-3,NESA|T4.2.1,NESA|T5.4.4,NESA|T5.4.5,NESA|T5.5.4,NESA|T5.6.1,NESA|T7.5.2,NESA|T7.5.3,NIAv2|AM3,NIAv2|SS29,Rule-ID|SV-77663r1_rule,STIG-ID|ESXI-06-000002,TBA-FIISB|31.1,Vuln-ID|V-63173"
  see_also    : "https://dl.dod.cyber.mil/wp-content/uploads/stigs/zip/U_VMware_vSphere_6-0_ESXi_V1R5_STIG.zip"
  xsl_stmt    : "<xsl:template match=\"/\">"
  xsl_stmt    : "<xsl:for-each select=\"//audit:returnval\">"
  xsl_stmt    : "<xsl:choose>"
  xsl_stmt    : "<xsl:when test=\"audit:propSet/audit:val/audit:option[audit:key='DCUI.Access']\">"
